projects:
[{'title': 'Connecting electro-mechanics to improve the prediction of ventricular tachycardias in post-MI patients', 'date': {'start': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2020}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}}, 'description': 'Graduation Master Thesis - Medical Engineering
Track: Cardiovascular Biomechanics

Grade: 8.5/10

The COMBAT-VT project aims to be better able to predict ventricular tachycardia
(VT) occurrences in patients who suffer from a chronic myocardial infarction (MI), by developing
an electro-mechanical (EM) Finite Element (FE) model of the heart and study the potential ef-
fects of mechanical changes on VT-risk. Therefore, this model should be bidirectionally coupled to
capture both forward electro-mechanical as well as backwards mechano-electrical feedback (MEF)
systems. It is essential that a suitable FE software package is chosen that offers the most optimal
modeling tools for this purpose. Because the CARPentry Modeling Environment (CME) is a very
promising candidate, consisting of electrical, mechanical and bidirectional electro-mechanical cou-
pling tools, it is extensively evaluated in this thesis. The emphasis will be on mechanics as this
has not yet been validated before.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Hilke', 'last_name': 'Straatman', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Master Student Medical Engineering at Eindhoven University of Technology'}]}, {'title': 'Modelling the Effects of Propofol on Cardiovascular Components', 'date': {'start': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}, 'end': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}}, 'description': 'Bachelor eind project in de groep Cardiovasculaire Biomechanica aan de Technische Universiteit Eindhoven
